english:
  title: Lamenting the Passing of Flowers
  author: Seok Won-gam
  language: eng
  text: |-
    On the twenty-sixth day of the twelfth moon I entered the city walls—
    turned my head and spring was already seventy-three days old.
    Last year and this year both flow like rivers,
    yesterday and today rush past like galloping steeds.

    Yesterday I watched the flowers beginning to open,
    today I watch them fading away.
    Flowers that bloom and fall leave no time for grieving,
    spring that comes and goes—who can hold it fast?

    The world sees only flowers opening and closing,
    not knowing their own bodies mirror the blooms.
    Did you not see how at dawn men boast before their mirrors of ruddy cheeks,
    yet by evening hurry toward the northern grave, hastening their funeral drums?

    Believe this truth when flowers bloom and fall:
    they speak plainly of impermanence,
    the ceaseless law that binds us all.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: '北邙 (northern grave): A reference to the famous cemetery north of Luoyang, symbolizing death and the grave'
  - key: ''
    value: '無常法 (impermanence): A Buddhist concept central to the poem''s meditation on the transient nature of all phenomena'
